segments.text: Was that at A&M or some other institution?
Another institution.
I turned it down because I wanted to be with Dr. Francis Moore.
And then I had another job offered in 31 that I turned down.
I went to that place and investigated.
Where was that?
Research, where the Agricultural Experiment Station had a subdivision.
And I turned it down.
But Dr. Francis was perturbed and went over to the president's office trying to get a raise.
And I wrote him a note.
I said, I'm not asking for a raise for this.
I'm just telling you that I'm satisfied here, and I'm going to stay.
But he gave me a raise, and he didn't wharten.
And it bothered him.
Later on he found out that Wharton wasn't getting that raise.
I don't know who called his attention to him, if it was Wharton or somebody else.
But he said that we came here on the same basis and should be on the same basis.
That's a Wharton seven?
No, Dr. Francis.
Oh, but I'm a little confused now.
Wharton did not get a raise.
No, he did not.
And you did?
Yes.
But I don't know just exactly why that came about in 35.
If I did, I've forgotten.
Don't you think Dr. Francis had something to do with it?
Well, he had to approve it.
He was dean.
And I don't know whether Dr. Marsteller had anything to do with it.
I can't answer that.
I don't know what...
I know this, that I didn't know the...

The ramifications on the responsibilities of head of a department, apparently, because Dean Bolton called me, asked me, told me that I was supposed to attend academic council meetings, but no one had ever told me about it.
And I missed one or two before I started going.
But that's a long time ago, I don't recall it.
Oh, except this, that in 36, I had been going to summer school in, I think I went in 29.
I spent a summer away from here at the University of Chicago taking special courses in physiology and biochemistry.
And then in 34, I was employed by the city of Dallas on meat inspection for the summer.
And one summer I helped
Dr. Francis turned a course over to me to teach.
He was supposed to teach it in the summer.
I taught it in his place.
That was in 1933, I believe.
I think it was in the Depression, either 1932 or 1933.
In 1934 I worked for the city of Dallas.
Dr. Francis died on June 28, 1936, and I was in Austin at the University of Texas taking two courses, one in physics and one in pharmacy.
And Ed's department was supposed to be on a twelve-month basis, and I'd been out
on a nine-month basis up until then.
But I knew my yearly salary, and they paid to me in the nine months.
I didn't apply for a leave of absence.
I spoke to Dr. Francis.
He said, sure, it would.
And that was enough as far as he was concerned.
And so at his funeral, Dr. Marsteller told me, he says,
Do you know you're supposed to be on 12 months basis?
I said, they paid me a nine, Dr. Marcell.
He said, well, you're supposed to.
Evidently, the fiscal office had called his attention to it, that I was supposed to be on 12 months.
And no one told you that?
No.
It was an error on the fiscal department.
They, of course, never made a mistake, but they did that one time.
So they dropped it.
They said, drop it.
Forget about it.
So after then, I applied for leave of absence.
But in other words, they wanted you to stay the extra three months in the summer, but keep you at the same nine-month salary.
Heads departments were supposed to be on 12 months duty.
That's right.
I don't recall my salary.
I don't know whether I
got a raise that year or not, I don't recall.
Maybe I did.
They paid me nine months, nine equal installments.
Nothing more was said about it.
I don't believe we could get by the fiscal department nowadays with that.
Back in 1935 when you took over that department, do you recall what
what your aims were, what you thought you should do with that department?
I don't recall now if I did.
Life went on about as usual, but I think I started probably with the idea of reorganizing courses.
When 37, when Dr. Marsteller, or fall of 36, I don't know when he asked me then, or in 37, whether I wanted to change anything.
I had several, I'll say, several changes.
During what those changes were?
Well, increasing the hours and changing the hours on some courses, yes.
We went from a four hour laboratory in toxicology, as I recall.
Back in those days you had two hour laboratories or four hour laboratories.
I asked for a three hour laboratory.
They wouldn't give it to me.
Joe Howell was Why did you want a three hour laboratory?
Because four was too long and two was too short.
I see.
The material we had to teach in that particular course
It was just a waste of time, to me, that fourth hour, because four hours is entirely too long for a laboratory period, the way we are teaching it.
So Joe Howell says, no, he says, you'll run our block system on scheduling.
And Joe Howell did all the scheduling.
He was a wizard at constructing schedules.
But I can see in one part in his favor that you had a two or four hour lab.
And if you put a three hours, you lose.
You waste that hour you can't schedule.
So if you have a one, four hour lab per week, you've got one hour there that you can't block off another course.
So I said, well, Joe,

If I had previously talked with Dr. Eads, who came into the department in the fall of 36, following his graduation in 36, in June 36, or May, I said, George Eads and I had discussed that if you wouldn't let us have it in the regular one to five, it would go to six o'clock.
I said, well, Joe, would it,
be all right if we went from three to six?"
He says, yeah, if you want to do that.
So we've had three hour labs ever since.
And there are many three hour laboratories now.
But I think that's true of other institutions.
But that's one change I recall that it looked like we were going to have a lot of difficulty with.
We didn't, and then we changed the hours on some courses and decreased it on some and increased it on others.
I recall that.
How about new faculty members?
Well, we added Eads that fall.
How many did you start out with in that department when you were chairman?
One.
That's you.
That's right.
When I came here in 26, there were four departments.
and six staff members for the entire School of Veterinary Medicine.
But EADS came in and then we added a third member I guess in 38 or 39, I don't recall, Herbert Ott.
And then Ott went to the
wanted to go into service, and he spent most of the war at Billy Bidd prison camp.
But he's in practicing California now, fortunately.
He got out of it.
He had charge of all the buffalo and things like that for all the meat supply for that, in that prison camp.
But,
And then Henry Kozyski, he changed his name to Keane, I believe.
He was Polish.
And why he changed his name is beyond me.
I don't think anyone ever knew why, unless it was his wife.
He married a girl from Bremont, I believe, or Waco, somewhere up there.
When did he come?
He came in...
probably 40, and stayed for a couple of years, and then he wanted to go in service.
So he is your third department member.
Yes.
And then he went to China and spent, went in the service, and quite a bit of it was in China.
Gee, yes.
And he had quite an experience, too.
He came back, and we tried to get him back, and he was a good man.
He was from Michigan.
But he decided he wanted to get into public health work.
And so I think he went down to Panama.
I forget what, some tropical area.
But then, I don't know, it was gradually added here and there.
How many faculty members did you have when you retired in your department?
I'd say eight or ten, something like that.
Eight or nine.
So you went from one to eight or nine in thirty-one years.
I'm not past the exact number, but oh goodness, you must have twenty or more now.
So that's one of the changes that you witnessed, this great expansion in your department.
Yes, and then the method of teaching.
As students increased the classes, we had to modify the method of teaching.
Okay, tell me about that.
What specifically, in your book you talk about electronic equipment.
Yes.
What kind of electronic equipment?
Dr. Reeds and I were both interested in presenting things or amplifying sounds of the heart and peristalsis and the gastrointestinal tract.
So we wanted a very superior instrument to do that with.
And someone had come out with a Mako, M-A-I-C-O, heartbeat pickup specifically for the heart and frequency and the sounds.
And it turned out to be a, it was put out by sound.
And we got, we were not responsible for picking that company solely.
We got literature from, corresponding with other veterinary colleges,
particular at Cornell about the type of instruments.
And I had gone to a workshop a couple of weeks up in Ithaca at Cornell University, got some pointers there, and we had already gotten into some of this other work before we went up there.
But we got into it more after going up there,
I think of their schools, Cornell was one of the leaders, and Minnesota was another one, but they got into the electronic method.
So we contacted Dutch Dillingham, who was a professor in electrical engineering, a graduate here of 1922, and a friend of mine.
Dutch went over the material, and he picked out the sound incorporated instrument.
And it turned out to be very delicate and was very suitable.
In fact, I liked it much better than one had at Cornell.
But we used Dutch as a kind of a consultant on material, and it paid off.
We'd never order anything without his approval.
We wanted a sound recorder.
He said, now listen, what kind of money do you have?
He said, we played around with some of these cheap instruments.
He had charge of the radio.
He said, we finally had to put a, he says, don't touch it.
unless you have $1,000 to spend.
$1,000 back in those days was pretty big money.
You could buy a sound recorder for $150, $200.
Maybe somehow it was cheaper than that, I don't know.
But he says, don't fool with them.
He says, we tried several up there in that radio, and said we finally had to get a good sound recorder, to get a good tape.
We had to spend...
I've forgotten, but he said it was over a thousand dollars, well over a thousand dollars.
He said, don't touch them unless you've got that much money.
But we didn't have it.
So we sidetracked that for a while, but oh, it made our class much more interesting for swallowing.
Even with the swallowing air, what we

some, we thought of doing this, that since you could hear those, the gurgling sounds of that air going into the cardiac portion of the stomach, and, or drinking water, you could hear it splash down here.
And you could magnify, amplify that thing, the whole class could hear almost every bubble.
Very interesting.
Very interesting, and so...
I don't know whether the students suggested, let him drink a Coke.
Of course, well, they'd carbonate it, and I tell you, it sounded like a boiler factory.
Oh, you could amplify that thing.
They'd blast it.
And so you could get the students' attention much more, and we'd let students use them.
We had two of them.
And once in a while, if they'd get damp, we'd have to send them in.
And one thing about it, we learned that
rubber diaphragm around it, so as if we put it down on a heart or something or on blood or anything fluid.
We dare not get that thing damp.
And like our amplifiers, Dutch told us, says, don't you ever get that damp.
And the water spilled on it, says, it'll
Well, the boys wanted those things for amplification on these dancers, and some of them had dancers, see, in the A&M student chapter of the AVMA.
I let them have it.
And one of them was off a little bit.
I think somebody spilled a Coke or something on the thing, and so I couldn't let them have it.
And because of that, I was worn.
It was my era.
But there was more and more demand.
And then other than that, somebody else wanted to borrow it.
Well, so we'll keep it here and keep it covered up to keep the air, keeping it from getting damp and then have it work.
But you've got to really.
warp sound of that thing, the horn.
Those things were about that high and that wide, the two amplifiers we used.
But they were excellent.
Were there any other electronic gadgetry that you used?
Oh, then we went to the Baylor University School of Medicine, the Physiology Department specifically.
The head of the department came from Yale and
He really went into electronics, and a private company was organized for putting those materials out.
They called it the physiograph.
First thing you know, in summer they were putting on courses in electronic reproduction and physiology, and people from all over the United States.
from the veterinary school.
I think they have a veterinary college in the United States.
One of the young instructors or something down there and took it back home and the whole veterinary education was changed and the physiology.
So now they have the department and Davis and the department and McCready who's head now.
had some ideas, and Mac Murray, they took that course.
Price went down when he resigned the deanship, why he went down to take that course at Baylor.
But I told him, I said, okay, you youngsters go after it.
I said, I'm too old to fool with some of that stuff.
I'm going to stay with some of this old material.
And I said, I still believe I can do some things that you all can't do with it.
sophisticated material.
And of course it racked my mind to think up something and racked their mind to refute my statement.
There's one thing that I know of that they can't do with that.
And I said, well, you're putting the students here and you're putting that material out.
It's a demonstration.
I said, I like the students to go in and get their hands
dirty and get them in, let them do a lot of the work.
That was my idea of teaching.

But it came to much of a demonstration, but now the students go, we have, they have the students, you can take up as many as six or seven in a group, and they've got little cubby holes, you know, where they work, and have that material, and they work by groups.
But all of them were wired together, and then those are hooked up to the demonstration room, the lecture room, and even out to the large animal.
You can take the horse, for example, instead of the horse, he's out in the building in the back.
And also with the TV station, they hook up, and it was just a closed circuit TV.
got hooked up to the clinic and hooked up to the autopsy room.
And the entire, every department involved, physiology, I know, and clinic.
When did this come back, about all this closed circuit?
Well, they were doing it by the time I retired.
It started beforehand.
We had gone physiographs.
We had physiographs stacked around like cordwood.
And we were going to that entirely.
In the meantime, I remember going up to St. Paul in Minneapolis.
The veterinary school is at St. Paul, the medical school in Minneapolis.
And I remember going up there, and they in the veterinary and the physiology department, they were still using the old man, a chymograph.
And they were doing a good job, but they felt that on graduate work, they'd let them do that.
But we were the first ones that let the students get into it and prepared that lab.
And I was putting our heads together to try to get that thing worked up architecturally to fit them.
And it is to fit the students.
And a lot of that was accomplished after, or it was in the process of being done when I retired.
But that whole
I think we started on electronics in 36, 37 I think, mostly 37, 38, somewhere along there.
We got interested in it.
In your department, was there a tendency toward more specialization over the years?
Yes, I used to think that we'd rotate.
instructors in physiology and pharmacology.
In fact, Dr. Schmidt has that in his statement.
He asked, who taught this, who taught that?
I said, Dr. Schmidt, my idea was rotating these men.
I said, if they go on and get promoted or go to some other school, they will have had experience in these others.
From my viewpoint, but now from
old from, Eads was more interested in pharmacology, I turned it over to him, gladly.
It's hard to teach.
And I'd take toxicology, and then one of the others would take physiology, Kazuski, and Farat, and then Kazuski.
And Eads and I both worked on physiology.
I still kept my hands in on physiology, what the others
I more or less took what the others left.
And I'd give them a choice of what they wanted to go into.
And because I think, first of all, they should be kept happy.
And I figured they'd stay there longer if they were happy and teaching what they wanted.
And if they wanted to rotate, it was all right.
But since then, it's become more and more
From year to year, it became more and more specialized.
Why do you think that is?
I don't know.
I took some courses.
The reason I wanted toxicology, because I had gone to Iowa State and had taken taxonomy, plant classification, from probably the leading taxonomist in the country, Dr. Pamel, L.H.
Pamel.
and noted botanist.
In fact, he was one of the first ones to work on cotton root rot here in the Experiment Station.
He and Dr. Francis became friends, and that was in the late 80s, early 90s.
And he was on loan from the Shaw Botanical Gardens of St. Louis to the college,
In fact, he initiated that work on cotton root rot.
Then Dr. Taubenhaus came in and took it over.
But then I had taken graduate work in poisonous plants from Dr. Pamel, a spire problems course.
And he, one of his daughters married
a veterinarian who was on the faculty at Gainesville, the University of Florida.
And he had become interested in poisonous plants, and so Dr. Pimel got to know practically every large animal practitioner in the state of Florida.
And he collected piles of specimens.
And he said, go through and classify those plants.
And he had just collected them the summer before, the winter before, see.
He'd take his vacations in January or February, and he'd go down there, and of course that still would have lush growth down in Florida.
But, oh, hundreds of plants.
And he says, classify those.
I learned some taxonomy.
That's the way to learn it.
And I had my desk in his office.
He had an office probably as big as this living room.
And so I had a microscope and a little desk table in one corner.
He was head ofthe botany department was on the fourth floor of Central Hall at Iowa State.
He had a heart condition, and he couldn't walk those steps.
He took me up there one day, and I said, Doc, he wants to show me something.
I don't recall now, and he says, no, I can make it.
We'll just have to stop and rest.
During and until we get to the top of each step, each level, we'd stop and rest a little.
But I was sure afraid of him.
But he, every day,
That is the five days or six days a week.
I think we were inside, outside the classes.
His desk would come in, he had a pile of specimens would be sent in.
He'd classify them.
He'd look at them at a glance and could tell what they were.
And he'd have the secretary dictate a letter to them.
and this plant is so-and-so, and so-and-so, and give something about the history of it, referring to the notes.
And it amazed me.
And up until that time, of course, I was animal-minded.
And I could see these, of course, in summer of 27.
That was before the Depression.
All the barns and the houses were well painted.
And some of those farms were just garden spots.
I'd take him out on Saturdays.
He wouldn't drive.
He didn't drive.
And he might get a letter.
It might be 50 or 60 miles from Ames, and we'd go out there.
I'd take him out there in my car.
And I got to seeing these hogs and these dairy cattle and these beef animals and these horses.
